<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Late mid day posts from Gordon Wrinn</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=260544" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/027801.html">Abashi! You've mentioned fixed Shaman and Bard Epic weapons, but...</a></B><P>

You have yet to address the issue of the useless effect of the Necro Epic Weapon (beyond saying that the save per tick would be fixed). It is still a useless effect, can you please state if this has also been repaired, or does the necro community need to keep posting why this effect is trash?<P>

<B>Once the save per tick problem is fixed in the next patch, I completely disagree that a free darkness series spell is "useless". That series is one of the staples of the necromancer class, and a way to cast it once or twice, even with a long casting time, for free, is quite a boon. <P>

I understand that there are those who disagree, but there have been people who've disagreed with the usefulness of every epic quest weapon that's been found so far. In short, it's not something we're considering changing.</B><P>

Agreed. Int doesn't have to be changed, but 40 more HP to give it 100 total HP/mana like the other weapons would be great.<P>

<B>We are modifying the stats on virtually all of the weapons, including the ones that haven't been found. I think that the cleric weapon is the only one that's not being modified.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/027981.html">Why is it that dex does not affect how a weapon procs?</a></B><P>

Why is it that dex does not affect how a weapon procs??? <P>

<B>It does. The example in your post is not a large enough model to see the difference. You could certainly proc 5 times in a row even with minimum dex, but the chance is far less.<P>

Remember that previous successes or failures have nothing to do with the chance of future successes or failures. The fact that you just proc'd does not make the chance of your next proc any closer or further away, probabiltywise. <P>

Regarding the random number generator, people think that because streaks happen that there's some problems. Random does not mean equal and regular distribution over the course of the sample. In any 10 flips of a coin you still have a .1% chance of never having it come up "heads". The fact that you may sit down and flip a coin 10 times and not get "heads" doesn't mean that your coin flip isn't random.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028004.html">You guys are back in winter time, right?</a></B><P>

I live in the UK, and last Sunday we put our clocks back an hour, going from British Summer Time (BST) to Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).
I understood that the USA changed times on the same date, except for 3 states (what's up with that? <P>

<B>I've lived in Arizona and Indiana.<P>

Indiana doesn't change because they are so close to the time line, that if they did it would still be light out at 10pm. <P>

Michigan (where I've also lived) does change for daylight savings time. It's very eerie to be sitting outside at 10pm reading a book.<P>

Arizona doesn't change due to the heat. Arizonan's don't want more "daylight" in their day. The sooner it gets dark in the summer the sooner it cools off and people can go outside. It gets dark around 8:30pm in the summer, and it's still frequently above 100F (~38C) at midnight.<P>

But to answer your question, yes, we've changed our clocks. We're back to GMT-8.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028083.html">Who has retired / put their character on hold due to 51+ lvl time requirements?</a></B><P>

After 6 hours in both Skyfire Moutains and Burningwoods I noticed that my EXP moved maybe 1 - 2 pixels. The only noticable EXP gain I have gotten since passing lvl 51 was in Seb after a 2 hour wait to get a group together. My druid is taking a small vacation while I work on my Monk or Rogue. I dont know if I can be classified as a "Casual" player. I am on almost every night but the time required to get to some of the better places for exp are a deterrent. <P>

I saw the "I am retiring my lvl 55 Enchanter" and wanted to know who else is deterred by the time needed to gain the higher lvls.<P>

<B>Just my opinion, but if you play for the express purpose of maxing out, you're setting yourself up for disappointment. Remember back before the level limit was raised when thousands of people were perfectly happy not to advance at all for months when they were 50th level, and how some of those same people got upset a week or two after we raised the limit when they weren't advancing fast enough.<P>

If someone feels free to go out and have fun without advancement, I don't see why they can't do the same when advancement can occur. It's my feeling that if people play the game to adventure and hang out with friends like they were doing before they could advance, advancement would still occur without the need to look at the bar after each kill.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028089.html">Is EQ slowly turning into a 50+ only club ?</a></B><P>

I don`t know if it`s only me noticing or I`m just quite delusional, but after Halloween`s little event, I am noticing more and more that EQ is turning into a highbie game. <P>

<B>Please remember that the lower levels are a transitional period. People move through them, and once they are through them, they move on to other places. For this reason, there's always been suitable in-game content for lower level folks, as people keep moving out of the lower levels.<P>

It's the high level game that is most in need of new content due to the growing number of "members" of that range. <P>

That said, we'd certainly like to see more dynamic events for the lower level folks. We have the ability now to limit who can attack gm-controlled NPCs, and it would definitely be nice to employ that more. Of course, that's gm-controlled NPCs only. Computer controlled NPCs remain attackable by everyone.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028120.html">Gordon, Alan. MoB Backstab needs to be looked at!</a></B><P>

Last night while running from a level 18 orc mercenary in HH he Backstabbed me for 120DMG!!! I REALLY think you guys need to do some testing on MoB backstabbing to make sure it is working as intended.<P>

<B>That sounds about right. I guess the moral of the story is: Don't turn your back on a rogue :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028098.html">Magic: the Gathering (TM)</a></B><P>

who plays?<P>

<B>We have a ton of people in house who play, but I've never personally gotten into it. I'm not much of a collector.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
